      &lt;p&gt;Fine then, Glenn, here it is plain answer:&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
a. Ye=
s if you define RESTFulness as a badge that certifies you follow the rules.=
 Yes, you can earn that badge only in your server and forget about the clie=
nt.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
b. NO, if you define RESTFulness as the achievement of the exp=
ected quality properties you seek for when using REST. And that NO is becau=
se the rules are made to achieve a way of interaction between the component=
s, and one of those components is the client. &lt;br&gt;


&lt;br&gt;
In other words, c=
lient matters.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
As I had been posting here, one component may not b=
ehave by the rules, but if that is free license the architect is aware of a=
nd it is reasonable so that the impact will not break the business goals, t=
hat is fine. But if you need a system where clients behave correctly, and y=
ou don&#39;t control the clients, then your architecture must have controls=
 and policy enforcement to avoid those spoiled clients from ruining you day=
. If not, your system will not get to its goal and it will be a failure, ev=
en if your server is made by the REST book. &lt;br&gt;


&lt;br&gt;
REST stops when it =
defines the constrains and promises quality properties, but life goes on, a=
nd the rest of the system is still to be constructed. Having just one serve=
r following REST rules is just one step. And let me clarify this: It should=
 not be part of the server&#39;s job to assure the client is working as it =
should. It may help, but we can have several layers that can add controls a=
nd enforce policies. There is far more in an system than just one server an=
d one client.&lt;br&gt;


&lt;br&gt;
Finally: I feel the discussion confuses an App, wi=
th a Server, with a System, with a API. When we talk about a server doing i=
ts part, sounds like we are talking about an API. Is it that? Yes, we can e=
xpose a REST like API, but then we need a client to consume it. A system is=
 something far more complex, where all components, including clients, may a=
ffect other components. Butterfly effect, that is called.&lt;br&gt;


&lt;br&gt;
Well, =
this was not a short and sweet answer, and I feel I&#39;m repeating myself =
here. But it is truly a more deep discussion than just earning a badge.&lt;br&gt;=

&lt;br&gt;
Cheers&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
William.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br&gt;
